{"data":[{"type":"questionAttempts","id":"17564909","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionAttempts/17564909"},"attributes":{"position":0,"marks":1,"score":1,"answeredAt":"2025-09-29T23:20:08+09:30","options":[1],"response":null,"finalizedAt":"2025-09-29T23:20:08+09:30"},"relationships":{"user":{"data":{"type":"users","id":"50098"}},"questionSession":{"data":null},"session":{"data":null},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17166"}},"bookmark":{"data":null}}}],"included":[{"type":"questions","id":"17166","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questions/17166"},"attributes":{"optionProportions":[0.56,0.29,0.08,0.03,0.04]},"relationships":{"item":{"data":{"type":"items","id":"9856"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105662"}}}},{"type":"items","id":"9856","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/items/9856"},"attributes":{"contentType":"question"},"relationships":{"content":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17166"}},"activeRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88108"}},"tags":{"data":[{"type":"tags","id":"23"},{"type":"tags","id":"65"},{"type":"tags","id":"72"},{"type":"tags","id":"76"},{"type":"tags","id":"1196"},{"type":"tags","id":"4517"},{"type":"tags","id":"4980"},{"type":"tags","id":"10779"},{"type":"tags","id":"10781"},{"type":"tags","id":"11159"},{"type":"tags","id":"11634"},{"type":"tags","id":"11950"},{"type":"tags","id":"12799"}]},"contributions":{"data":[{"type":"contributions","id":"23094"},{"type":"contributions","id":"35620"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37122"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37504"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37767"},{"type":"contributions","id":"37832"},{"type":"contributions","id":"43688"},{"type":"contributions","id":"45452"}]}},"meta":{"canRevise":false,"canManage":false,"canDelete":false}},{"type":"questionRevisions","id":"105662","links":{"self":"https://app.emedici.com/api/questionRevisions/105662"},"attributes":{"stem":"\u003Cp\u003EA 32-year-old woman presents to the General Practice clinic requesting non-invasive prenatal testing. She is eight weeks pregnant according to her last menstrual period. She has had a dating ultrasound at six weeks which has confirmed fetal viability. This is her first pregnancy. She has no significant medical history and takes only folate supplements. She works as an accountant. On examination, she appears well with vital signs within normal limits. Her body mass index is 24 kg/m\u003Csup\u003E2\u003C/sup\u003E.\u003C/p\u003E","stemQuestion":"Which one of the following should be offered alongside non-invasive prenatal testing?","responseType":"sba","marks":1,"options":["Combined first trimester screening 11-14 weeks","Ultrasound scan prior to NIPT","Maternal serum screening from 10 weeks","Amniocentesis at 15 weeks","Chorionic villus sampling at 11 weeks"],"correctOptions":[1],"correctResponses":[],"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis patient is requesting non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) in early pregnancy. While NIPT is highly accurate for detecting common chromosomal abnormalities, it should not be performed in isolation. NIPT only detects possible chromosomal abnormalities and does not detect structural fetal anomalies such as spina bifida and anencephaly that will have normal fetal chromosome testing. \u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EUltrasound scan prior to NIPT \u003C/strong\u003E is essential before proceeding with NIPT. It confirms fetal viability and can detect major structural anomalies that will not be detected on chromosomal testing alone such as neural tube defects (spina bifida, anencephaly). This information is crucial before proceeding with the more expensive NIPT.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003ECombined first trimester screening\u003C/strong\u003E (CFTS) would be unnecessary if NIPT is being performed, as both tests screen for chromosomal abnormalities. NIPT has superior sensitivity and specificity compared to CFTS for detecting trisomies 21, 18, and 13.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMaternal serum screening\u003C/strong\u003E alone would be inappropriate as it has lower sensitivity than NIPT and is typically part of CFTS. It would be redundant if NIPT is being performed.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EBoth \u003Cstrong\u003EChorionic villus sampling \u003C/strong\u003Eand \u003Cstrong\u003Eamniocentesis\u003C/strong\u003E are invasive diagnostic tests that carries a small risk of miscarriage. They would only be offered if NIPT or other screening tests suggested an increased risk of chromosomal abnormality.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003ENIPT can be performed from 10 weeks gestation and has a detection rate of over 99% for trisomy 21. However, it is important to counsel patients that NIPT is a screening test, not a diagnostic test, and that positive results require confirmation with diagnostic testing. NIPT also does not detect fetal structural abnormalities or fetal viability.\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":["","","","",""],"learningPoints":["Non-invasive prenatal testing (NIPT) should be accompanied by an ultrasound to confirm viability and check for major structural anomalies.","NIPT is highly sensitive for common chromosomal abnormalities but does not detect structural anomalies.","Early ultrasound assessment provides important information about gestational age, viability, and multiple pregnancy.","It is not recommended to perform both CFTS and NIPT testing as both are screening tests with NIPT outperforming the CFTS"],"references":["Royal Australian and New Zealand College of Obstetricians and Gynaecologists. Fetal anomalies: clinical guideline [Internet]. Melbourne (AU): RANZCOG; 2016 [cited 2024 Dec 10]. Available from: https://ranzcog.edu.au/wp-content/uploads/Fetal-Anomalies-Clinical-Guideline.pdf"]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"88108"}},"question":{"data":{"type":"questions","id":"17166"}},"stemMedia":{"data":[]},"explanationMedia":{"data":[]}}},{"t